From: Dan Williams <dan.j.williams@intel.com>
Date: Tue, 16 Jan 2018 17:24:35 -0800
Subject: x86, get_user: use pointer masking to limit speculation
Git-repo: git://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/djbw/linux.git
Git-commit: 582db732ea168afb92205ca3c81b253324c3453b
Patch-mainline: Queued in subsystem maintainer repository
References: bsc#1068032 CVE-2017-5715

Quoting Linus:

    I do think that it would be a good idea to very expressly document
    the fact that it's not that the user access itself is unsafe. I do
    agree that things like "get_user()" want to be protected, but not
    because of any direct bugs or problems with get_user() and friends,
    but simply because get_user() is an excellent source of a pointer
    that is obviously controlled from a potentially attacking user
    space. So it's a prime candidate for then finding _subsequent_
    accesses that can then be used to perturb the cache.

Unlike the '__get_user' case 'get_user' includes the address limit check
near the pointer de-reference. With that locality the speculation can be
mitigated with pointer narrowing rather than a barrier. Where the
narrowing is performed by:

	cmp %limit, %ptr
	sbb %mask, %mask
	and %mask, %ptr

With respect to speculation the value of %ptr is either less than %limit
or NULL.

